1 Modifying Theme Components

  • element_text() headings . , , , , hjust, vjust, angle and lineheight .
base_t <- base + labs(title = "This is a ggplot") + xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL)
grid.arrange(
base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16)),
base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", colour = "red")),
base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 1)), ncol = 3)

text margin margin() . margin() , top(t), right(r), bottom(b) and left(l) sides of the text.

# The margins here look asymmetric because there are also plot margins
grid.arrange(
base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(margin = margin())), #   
base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10, b = 10))), #     
base_t + theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(r = 10))), ncol = 3)

2.2 Axis Elements

Caption for the picture.

axis.text (and axis. title) .:axis.text, axis.text.x and axis.text.y. .

df <- data.frame(x = 1:3, y = 1:3)
base <- ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) + geom_point()

# Accentuate the axes
base + theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "grey50", size = 1))

# Style both x and y axis labels
base + theme(axis.text = element_text(color = "blue", size = 12))

# Useful for long labels
base + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = -90, vjust = 0.5))

x . . hjust = 0 vjust = 1 .

df <- data.frame(
  x = c("label", "a long label", "an even longer label"),
  y = 1:3
)
base <- ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) + geom_point()
base

base +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = -30, vjust = 1, hjust = 0)) +
  xlab(NULL) +
  ylab(NULL)

2.3 Legend Elements

Caption for the picture.

df <- data.frame(x = 1:4, y = 1:4, z = rep(c("a", "b"), each = 2))
base <- ggplot(df, aes(x, y, colour = z)) + geom_point()
grid.arrange(
base + theme(
  legend.background = element_rect(
    fill = "lemonchiffon",
    colour = "grey50",
    size = 1
  )
),
base + theme(
  legend.key = element_rect(color = "grey50"),
  legend.key.width = unit(0.9, "cm"),
  legend.key.height = unit(0.75, "cm")
),
base + theme(
  legend.text = element_text(size = 15),
  legend.title = element_text(size = 15, face = "bold")
), ncol = 3)

legned.position, legend.direction, legend.justification, legend.box .

2.4 Panel Elements

Caption for the picture.

panel.background panel.border background border . panel.border fill = NA .

base <- ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) + geom_point()
grid.arrange(
# Modify background
base + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue")),
# Tweak major grid lines
base + theme(
  panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray60", size = 0.8)
),
# Just in one direction
base + theme(
  panel.grid.major.x = element_line(color = "gray60", size = 0.8)
), ncol = 3)

base2 <- base + theme(plot.background = element_rect(colour = "grey50"))
grid.arrange(
# Wide screen
base2 + theme(aspect.ratio = 9/16), #aspect ratio :  
# Long and skiny
base2 + theme(aspect.ratio = 2/1),
# Square
base2 + theme(aspect.ratio = 1), ncol = 3)

2.5 Facetting Elements

Caption for the picture.

panel.margin panel.spacing .

strip.text.x facet_wrat() facet_grid() strip.text.y facet_grid() .

df <- data.frame(x = 1:4, y = 1:4, z = c("a", "a", "b", "b"))
base_f <- ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~z)
base_f

base_f + theme(panel.spacing = unit(0.5, "in"))

base_f + theme(
  strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey20", color = "grey80", size = 1),
  strip.text = element_text(colour = "white")
)

2.6 Exercises

  1. theme dark() makes the inside of the plot dark, but not the outside. Change the plot background to black, and then update the text settings so you can still read the labels.
base_f + theme_dark() + 
  theme(
  plot.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
  axis.text = element_text(colour = "white"),
  axis.title = element_text(colour = "white"),
  axis.ticks = element_line(colour = "white")
                              )

  1. Make an elegant theme that uses linen as the background colour and a serif font for the text.
base_f + 
  ggtitle("Elegant theme using linen and serif font") +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "linen"),
        plot.title = element_text(family = "serif"))

  1. Systematically explore the effects of hjust when you have a multiline title. Why doesnt vjust do anything?
base_f + 
  ggtitle("Elegant theme using linen and serif font", subtitle = "Explor the effects of hjust") +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "linen"),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif"))
